    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. but i keep seeing people call it \"spooky action at a distance.\" why did einstein call it that? is there something actually weird or unexplainable about how they stay connected?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Einstein called it \"spooky action at a distance\" because, to him, it seemed to violate the principle that nothing can travel faster than the speed of light. He was deeply bothered by the instantaneous connection between entangled particles, which seemed to imply some sort of hidden, faster-than-light communication.  The weirdness, or what makes it so mind-bending, is precisely that instantaneous correlation.  While the correlation is real, it's crucial to understand that you *cannot* use entanglement to send actual information faster than light.",
      "source": "target",
