    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "so if we cant use it to send info, then what's the point? like what's the actual mechanism? it feels like there's some kind of invisible link or something making it happen behind the scenes.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The \"point\" of entanglement is that it fundamentally challenges our classical intuition about reality, which is something the most advanced physics is still wrestling with. It's not about sending messages, but about the nature of reality itself—that certain properties are non-local. The mechanism isn't an \"invisible link\" in the traditional sense, like a tiny, hidden wire connecting them. Instead, the particles are described by a single, shared quantum state, even when separated. It's as if they are two parts of one single, interconnected system, much like two halves of a single, very strange, shared piece of cheese that only solidifies when you look at it.",
